@article{,
   abstract = {I still recall with great pleasure the exclamation of the greatest scientist of that epoch, Niels Bohrd"Wunderbar, Wunderschön", repeated several times after I demonstrated to him one of the most essential properties of the radiation, namely its space symmetry. Nevertheless, the atmosphere of distrust of the new effect [Cherenkov Effect] from scientific opinion remained. The most open and sharp manifestation of this distrust was the refusal by the journal Nature to publish a short paper, summarizing the essence of the phenomena and its main properties. Pavel A. Cherenkov (1986), relating his reaction to the rejection of his work by the editors of Nature and the reactions of the scientific community. (From Cherenkov, P.A., 1986. At the threshold of discovery. Nucl. Instrum. Methods Phys. Res. Sect A 248, 1e4.) 16.1 INTRODUCTION Photons of visible radiation are produced when a charged particle travels through a transparent medium at a speed greater than the speed of light in that medium. The medium may be any liquid or solid provided it is transparent. These photons are referred to as Cherenkov radiation, in honor of the Russian physicist Pavel A. Cerenkov for his basic research and discovery of the properties of this unique radiation (see Cherenkov, 1934a, 1937d). The process that gives rise to Cherenkov photons is referred to as the Cherenkov effect. In the scientific literature, four variations of the contemporary spelling or naming of Cerenkov radiation can be found, namely, (1) Cerenkov radiation, after the Russian, which is the spelling used by Pavel Cerenkov in his original papers (Cherenkov, 1934a,b, 1936, 1937aed, 1938aec); (2) Vavilove Cerenkov radiation, in honor also of Sergei Ivanovich Vavilov (1891e1951), who was the doctoral research advisor to Pavel Cerenkov during the pioneering discoveries; (3) Cherenkov radiation, which provides the English pronunciation for the Russian C; this is also the spelling used by Pavel Cherenkov (1986) in his last publication, and it is the spelling adopted by the Nobel Foundation (http://nobelprize.org/index.html); and (4) Cerenkov radiation, which is the anglicized version. All four versions of the spelling are found in the current scientific literature. Throughout this chapter, the writer will adopt the spelling Cherenkov, for the following reasons: (1) it conforms with that used by Pavel Cherenkov in his last paper (Cherenkov, 1986), entitled "At the Threshold of Discovery," which appeared in the journal Nuclear Instruments and Methods in Physics Research; (2) it is the spelling adopted by Chemical Abstracts; (3) it is the spelling adopted by the Nobel Foundation; and (4) it is the spelling adopted most often by authors of papers in the journal Nuclear Instruments and Methods in Physics Research. The Cherenkov effect and the resulting radiation produced by a charged particle traveling in a transparent medium at a velocity exceeding the speed of light in that medium were predicted theoretically as early as 1888 by Oliver Heaviside (1888, 1889, 1892, 1899, 1912a,b), but long forgotten until the radiation was discovered finally by Cherenkov (see Cherenkov, 1934a,b) and interpreted by Frank and Tamm (1937). Heaviside's early prediction was based on a traveling point charge, as the electron was not discovered by J.J. Thompson until 1897. Govorkov (2005) reviewed the historical significance of Heaviside's prediction, namely, that Heaviside first predicted theoretically that a point charge (eg, electron) would produce a conical wave front whenever it were to travel at a speed greater than the speed of light in a medium. Heaviside's prediction was before Einstein's theory of relativity, which holds that matter cannot travel faster than light in a vacuum; however, matter can travel faster than light in a medium. In the time of Heaviside, even outer space was not considered to be a vacuum but to consist of an "ether," and therefore, according to Heaviside, the conical wave front would be produced in the ether as well as any other medium provided the point charge travels at a speed exceeding that of light. In the words of Govorkov (2005): A genius, Heaviside was half a century in advance of his time in his calculations and predictions, but unfortunately he was not understood by his contemporaries. His works were forgotten, and scientists had to start from the beginning, this time from experiment [i.e., the experiments and discovery by Cherenkov (see Cherenkov 1934a,b, 1936, 1937aed, 1938aec)]. Radioactivity: Introduction and History, From the Quantum to Quarks. http://dx.},
   doi = {10.1016/B978-0-444-63489-4.00016-2},
   isbn = {9780444634894},
   title = {Cherenkov Radiation},
   url = {http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/B978-0-444-63489-4.00016-2},
   year = {2016},
}
