@book_section{Radamson2018,
   abstract = {The aim of this chapter is to review device scaling, which is the driving force for the development of complementary metal-oxide-semiconductor (CMOS) technology over the years until the end of the Semiconductor Industry Association Roadmap. At first, different types of device scaling will be presented together with the associated scaling law for the main device parameters. Based on the concept of the natural device length, it will be shown that there is better gate control over the channel for a vertical multiple gate fin-type of architecture compared with planar devices. The same goes for fully depleted (FD) silicon-on-insulator (SOI) technologies, using an ultrathin film and a thin buried oxide (BOX) layer. Ultimately, MOSFETs will take on a gate-all-around (GAA) nanowire (NW) configuration, possibly in a junctionless CMOS process. Later, lithography for downscaling is presented. In this section, the resolution enhancement techniques will be presented. Later, extreme ultraviolet lithography (EUVL) technology and electron beam lithography (EBL) will be described. In the next part, the necessity of so-called strain engineering will be briefly highlighted. Finally, possible scenarios for beyond CMOS devices will be discussed, including tunnel FETs (TFETs) and spintronic devices.},
