ering paper by Phil-ipp and Ehrenrich, 7 who calculated the optical constants of Al for the first time over an extended energy range, using experimental results together with interpolations. Their sum-rule check revealed a serious lack of oscil­ lator strength. We used one or another of three procedures for com­ parison of our data with those of other investigators. (1) If the absorption coefficient could be determined di­ rectly from the measured transmittance, and if μ val­ ues were available, a Kramers-Kronig analysis was performed with the absorption spectrum. (2) If only re­ flectance data were available in the infrared, visible and near-uv region, first the Kramers-Kronig relation was used to determine the phase change of the reflected beam, from which, together with the measured absorp­ tion in the vuv regime and in the x-ray region, 8 a com­ plete absorption spectrum was constructed. (3) For Au and Ag, the reflectance is great in the region between 20 eV and 50 eV; therefore the complete transmittance spectrum was constructed and a Kramers-Kronig rela­ tion was used to determine the phase change of the transmitted beam. 9 In Figs. 1-8, the final absorption coefficients μ are shown (full lines) as functions of photon energy. We do not present here, in detail, the origin or the analysis of the data finally chosen nor the way of combining them for use in the Kramers-Kronig analysis; for this, the interested reader is referred to Ref. 1. The data be-TABLE I. Summary of numerical evaluation of sum rules. n 0 = number of conduction electrons; Δn coid α ∫ ω core ω ε 2 (ω)dω, ω ∞re being the frequency of first onset of core transitions; ∆nk α ∫ ω ∞ K μ(ω)dω, ω K being the onset of K transitions; Z = total number of electrons; n eff (ε2) ∫ 0 ∞ ω ε 2 (ω)dω ; n eff (μ) α ∫ 0 ∞ μ(ω)dω; n eff (Imε-1) α ∫ 0 ∞ ω ε 2 /(ε 1 2 +ε 2 2)dω. The absolute values and the deviations from Z (in percent) are given. 742},
